SHEET 1 — RAMA HUB STRUCTURE
Purpose
The RAMA Hub is the central structural ring that all other systems attach to. It provides geometry, stability, and a standardized interface for assembly, expansion, and long‑term operations in orbit.

Core Geometry
Outer circumference: ~400 meters

Footprint: 15m × 20m per rim section

Height: 15 meters

Total rim sections: 20 identical modules forming a closed ring

Design principle: Pure structure — no interior use, no equipment, no utilities

Structural Philosophy
The Hub is intentionally empty and single‑purpose

It exists only to:

Hold shape

Provide attachment points

Support loads

Enable expansion

No systems are embedded into the Hub to avoid complexity, failure points, or redesign pressure

Assembly Logic
Built from 20 identical rim sections

Each section is:

Manufactured on Earth

Launched as a single unit

Connected in orbit using MOEs

The ring locks into a rigid, stable geometry once all sections are joined

Why This Matters
A clean, empty, structural‑only hub:

Reduces risk

Simplifies manufacturing

Makes scaling predictable

Allows any future system to attach without redesign

Keeps RAMA modular, repairable, and evolvable
